  :prose
"In 1962 four MIT students wired a PDP-1 to a modified oscilloscope and
wrote a two-player game where each player controlled a small
triangular spaceship with a thruster and a gun. The ships drifted in a
frictionless void around a central star whose gravity you had to
respect. Nine kilobytes of core memory. Two joysticks made from mercury
switches. It cost the university nothing and captured every hacker
within a three-state radius.

That game — Space War — is this chapter. You will build a ship with a
heading, a thrust, and a drift. You will discover the difference between
'the direction you are facing' and 'the direction you are moving.' You
will feel, in your thumbs, why real space is not like a road: press
forward once and you keep going forever.

Then you will add a moon, turn on `world/attract!`, and watch the ship
orbit. That is your first taste of gravitational feel — the arcade
version of Kepler's laws, at 60 frames per second.

---

## 3.1 The rotating ship

Before thrust, rotation. Left and right rotate; the ship faces where
its heading angle points.

```scheme
;; A triangular ship you can rotate with left/right.
(define ship-angle 0)   ;; radians, 0 = pointing right
(define (rotating-ship)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (set! ship-angle (- ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle 0.08)))
       (entity/pose! ship 'angle ship-angle)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)
       ;; Draw a heading arrow so we can SEE which way the ship faces.
       (paint-arrow (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship)
                    (+ (entity/x ship) (* 30 (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                    (+ (entity/y ship) (* 30 (geom/sin ship-angle)))))))
(big-bang rotating-ship)
```

`ship-angle` is a global variable holding radians. Zero points right;
pi/2 points down; pi points left; 3pi/2 points up. `geom/cos` and
`geom/sin` decompose the angle into x- and y-components of a unit
vector. That decomposition IS the vector math this chapter teaches.

`entity/pose! ship 'angle ship-angle` tells the sprite to rotate with
the heading — if we had a proper spaceship sprite, its nose would
follow the arrow.

Try holding 'left' for two seconds. The ship spins a full turn every
seven seconds at 0.08 radians per frame. That is 60 * 0.08 = 4.8
radians per second. A full rotation is 2*pi = 6.28 radians. So 6.28 /
4.8 = 1.3 seconds per rotation. Do the arithmetic; feel the number.

---

## 3.2 Add thrust

Now the ship can push itself in the direction it is facing.

```scheme
;; Rotate and thrust. Ship drifts forever in space.
(define ship-angle 0)
(define (thrusting-ship)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (entity/drag! ship 0)             ;; NO drag — space
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (set! ship-angle (- ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'a)
         ;; Add thrust in the direction of ship-angle.
         (let ((vx (car (entity/vel ship)))
               (vy (cadr (entity/vel ship)))
               (thrust 0.15))
           (entity/set-vel! ship
                            (+ vx (* thrust (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                            (+ vy (* thrust (geom/sin ship-angle))))))
       (entity/pose! ship 'angle ship-angle)
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)
       (paint-arrow (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship)
                    (+ (entity/x ship) (* 20 (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                    (+ (entity/y ship) (* 20 (geom/sin ship-angle))))))))

(big-bang thrusting-ship)
```

Read section 3.2 carefully. The velocity update is the important line:

```
(entity/set-vel! ship
                 (+ vx (* thrust (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                 (+ vy (* thrust (geom/sin ship-angle))))
```

We take the current velocity `(vx vy)`. We take the heading vector
`(cos ang, sin ang)`. We scale the heading by `thrust`. We add. That
is vector addition. The new velocity is the old velocity PLUS an
impulse in the facing direction.

This is why the ship drifts. Once you have accumulated `(vx=2, vy=-1)`
by thrusting up-and-to-the-right, releasing 'a' does not zero those
components. The ship coasts. To stop, you rotate 180 degrees and
thrust the same amount BACKWARD to cancel the velocity. Kids figure
this out in about ninety seconds and are proud of themselves.

`entity/drag! ship 0` disables the runtime's default drag. In space
there is nothing to push against; velocity persists. Set drag to 0.02
and try again — the ship slowly slows down without input. That
'friction' is a lie the game tells for playability. Real Space War
kept drag at zero, and pilots hated it, and loved it.

---

## 3.3 Heading is not velocity

Here is the pedagogical crux of vector math. Draw two arrows on the
screen: one for HEADING (where the ship faces), one for VELOCITY
(where the ship is moving).

```scheme
;; Show both arrows so the kid sees the difference.
(define ship-angle 0)
(define (two-arrows)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (entity/drag! ship 0)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (set! ship-angle (- ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'a)
         (let ((vx (car (entity/vel ship)))
               (vy (cadr (entity/vel ship))))
           (entity/set-vel! ship
                            (+ vx (* 0.15 (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                            (+ vy (* 0.15 (geom/sin ship-angle))))))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)
       ;; RED arrow — heading.
       (paint-arrow (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship)
                    (+ (entity/x ship) (* 30 (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                    (+ (entity/y ship) (* 30 (geom/sin ship-angle))))
       ;; BLUE arrow — velocity.
       (let ((vx (car (entity/vel ship)))
             (vy (cadr (entity/vel ship))))
         (paint-arrow (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship)
                      (+ (entity/x ship) (* 15 vx))
                      (+ (entity/y ship) (* 15 vy))))))))

(big-bang two-arrows)
```

Two arrows, one origin. Rotate the ship — the red arrow (heading)
swings around; the blue arrow (velocity) stays put. Thrust — the blue
arrow starts to grow in the heading direction. Rotate 180 and thrust
again — the blue arrow shrinks toward zero, then flips and grows in
the OTHER direction. The kid can literally see the vector algebra.

Appendix D (Heading vs Velocity — the Two-Arrow Diagram) formalizes
this into a poster you can tape to the wall.

---

## 3.4 Wrap-around

A ship that drifts off-screen is a lost ship. Classic arcade wraps the
world: fly off the right edge, appear on the left. The Motoi reference
does not yet expose a `world/wrap!` verb (see the design's gap-1 note),
so we roll it ourselves.

```scheme
;; Toroidal world: off-screen on the right = on-screen on the left.
(define ship-angle 0)
(define (wrapping-ship)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (entity/drag! ship 0)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (set! ship-angle (- ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'a)
         (let ((vx (car (entity/vel ship)))
               (vy (cadr (entity/vel ship))))
           (entity/set-vel! ship
                            (+ vx (* 0.15 (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                            (+ vy (* 0.15 (geom/sin ship-angle))))))
       (world/step)
       ;; Wrap horizontally at 0 / 320, vertically at 0 / 240.
       (let ((x (entity/x ship)) (y (entity/y ship)))
         (when (< x 0)   (entity/set-pos! ship (+ x 320) y))
         (when (> x 320) (entity/set-pos! ship (- x 320) y))
         (when (< y 0)   (entity/set-pos! ship x (+ y 240)))
         (when (> y 240) (entity/set-pos! ship x (- y 240))))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)))))

(big-bang wrapping-ship)
```

Four `when` clauses. Each checks one edge; if the ship crossed it, we
add or subtract the screen dimension. That is toroidal topology in
four lines. Every Asteroids-family game does this.

Nice property: the wrap is invisible to the physics. `entity/vel`
stays what it was; only position moves. So the ship's momentum
carries continuously across the wrap.

---

## 3.5 The moon (arcade gravity)

Now the fun part. Put a big body in the middle. Turn on gravitational
attraction.

```scheme
;; Ship + moon. Moon pulls ship. Ship orbits (if you thrust right).
(define ship-angle 0)
(define (ship-and-moon)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((moon (world/spawn 'moon 160 120))
        (ship (world/spawn 'ship 240 120)))
    (entity/shape! moon 'circle 20)
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 10)
    (entity/mass! moon 100)
    (entity/mass! ship 1)
    (entity/drag! ship 0)
    ;; Give the ship an initial tangential kick.
    (entity/set-vel! ship 0 -2.2)
    ;; Turn on radial attraction from the moon.
    (world/attract! ship (entity/x moon) (entity/y moon) 0.15)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (set! ship-angle (- ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle 0.08)))
       (when (input/down? 'a)
         (let ((vx (car (entity/vel ship)))
               (vy (cadr (entity/vel ship))))
           (entity/set-vel! ship
                            (+ vx (* 0.12 (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                            (+ vy (* 0.12 (geom/sin ship-angle))))))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'moon (entity/x moon) (entity/y moon) 40 40)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 10 10)))))

(big-bang ship-and-moon)
```

`world/attract! ship (entity/x moon) (entity/y moon) 0.15` says
'every frame, add a force toward the moon's position on ship, with
strength 0.15.' The strength number is not proper Newtonian G, but
it's inverse-square-like enough that orbits behave.

The initial `entity/set-vel! ship 0 -2.2` kicks the ship straight up
(y negative = up). With the moon pulling right (moon is to the left
of the ship's start position, moon at 160, ship at 240), the ship
curves left as it climbs, and if you tuned the tangential speed right
it enters a stable ellipse.

Try different initial y-velocities: 1.0 falls in; 2.2 orbits; 5.0
escapes. That is the elementary calculation of orbital energy — total
energy = kinetic + potential; if it exceeds zero the ship escapes.
Kids do not need to know the formula to feel it.

The ship's own thrust is available; a good pilot can adjust orbit
apogee and perigee by thrusting prograde (in the direction of motion)
or retrograde (against). This is the same mechanic astronauts use to
change orbit.

---

## 3.6 The four patterns in a space game

**Composition.** The ship is composed: shape, mass, drag, initial
velocity, attract-target. The moon is composed similarly with heavier
mass. Chapters 4-5 will compose bullets, enemies, health.

**Orchestration.** The frame loop orchestrates: poll heading input,
poll thrust input, integrate physics via `world/step`, wrap position,
draw. Note that wrap happens AFTER step; if we wrapped before step,
the ship would sometimes teleport mid-frame and physics could get
confused.

**In-routing.** Three buttons route to three handlers: left rotates,
right rotates, 'a' thrusts. Later ('b' fires) adds a fourth. Each
handler is small; each mutates one aspect of world state.

**Routing.** The `world/attract!` call is routing set up at spawn
time: 'every frame from now on, route a force from the moon to the
ship.' The runtime remembers the attraction and re-applies it. If we
had many moons and many ships, we would call attract for each pair.

---

## 3.7 Common desktop tasks

**Ship-tourism scoreboard.** A shop selling telescopes or space-themed
products embeds a small ship-and-moon minigame: pilot from Earth to
Moon in the fewest thrusts. Best time gets a display banner. The game
teaches orbital economy while it sells the product.

**Package-drift receipt animation.** After checkout, a small ship
carries the buyer's package sprite across the screen, drifting past
planets that represent the item's category. Physics-first branding.

---

## 3.8 Pitfalls

**The ship spins but does not move.** You forgot `entity/set-vel!` or
you passed the wrong arguments. Check that `(entity/vel ship)` is a
list `(vx vy)` and you are `car` and `cadr`-ing it correctly.

**The ship stops as soon as you release 'a'.** `entity/drag!` is
non-zero. Space has no drag. Set it to 0 unless you want a poor-man's
Newton's-first-law violation.

**The orbit spirals in.** Your initial tangential velocity is too low
— the ship falls into the moon. Increase `entity/set-vel! ship 0
-2.5` and try again.

**The orbit spirals out.** Initial velocity too high — escape
trajectory. Decrease.

**Rotation is jerky.** `0.08` radians per frame is a fine baseline;
below 0.04 feels slow, above 0.15 is spinny. Consider using
`tick/ease` to ramp rotation speed in the frames after button press,
so the ship 'settles into' its rotation rate. Chapter 6 (Feel) shows
exactly this.

**Coordinate confusion.** In screen space, y grows DOWN. `geom/sin
angle` returns positive values for angles in the second and third
quadrants (angle between 0 and pi radians), which point DOWN on the
screen. If your ship rotates the wrong way, remember: screen-y is
flipped from math-y.

---

## 3.9 Try this yourself

1. Add a second moon. Give the ship both attractions:
   `(world/attract! ship moon2-x moon2-y 0.10)`. Watch the ship
   figure-eight between them (three-body problem, in the small).
2. Add `world/wind! 0.05 0` — a solar wind. The ship drifts sideways
   without input. Does that ruin the game or make it more
   interesting?
3. Give the ship `entity/max-speed! ship 5` — cap the drift. Space
   with a speed limit is not-space, but it plays gently.
4. Replace the moon's `world/attract!` with `world/repel!` at the
   same strength — the moon becomes a shield generator. Fly around
   it; try to get close.
5. Add a fire button ('b'): each press spawns a small bullet with
   velocity = ship-velocity + heading * bullet-speed. Chapter 4
   covers this in depth.
6. Make the ship 'wrap' with fade-in on the new edge — spawn a ghost
   at the old position that fades over 15 frames.

---

## 3.10 What we built

A ship. A heading. A thrust. A drift. A wrap. A moon. Vector
decomposition into cos-and-sin components. `world/attract!` as arcade
gravity. Two-arrow visualization of heading versus velocity.

Next chapter: the ship stops moving, it stays put, but it FIRES. We
build cannons and projectiles. `phys/kinematics` finally earns its
name.")

